## How to use this template

This template is a starting point, not a finished document. Copy it, rename it, and fill the fields below. Delete the placeholder text once you have replaced it; leave the headings so the structure stays consistent across the company.

A template stops being a template the moment a real instance exists; that instance is the canonical document and this file is the source of the next one.

## Fields

- **Title** — what this instance is.
- **Owner** — the person responsible for keeping it current.
- **Audience** — who reads it.
- **Date** — the date the instance was created.
- **Status** — draft, current, retired.

## Body

The body of the document goes here. Use the section headings that match the type of document; the *Operating System Style Guide* records the conventions.

Where this template is for a recurring artefact (meeting notes, weekly update, monthly close), the body is short and structured. Where it is for a one-off (RFC, ADR, postmortem), the body is long-form prose.

## More definitions

- **In flight** — work that has been started but not yet shipped.
- **Shipped** — code that is in production, or a document that is in `current` status.
- **Blocked** — work that cannot progress until another piece of work or decision completes.
- **At risk** — work that is in flight but is not on track to ship in the planned window.
- **Done** — work that has shipped, has a passing test, has a record in the relevant log, and has been signed off by the relevant owner.

